This ethical and political purpose, however insufficient to explain the treatise as a whole, has powerfully influenced the treatment of considerable portions3. In exhibiting to his readers the great free people who alone among the nations had ever cast off the yoke once laid upon them, and caused a distinct recession of the Roman frontier, he would naturally use all his skill to idealize the vigorous and manly qualities standing in the sharpest contrast to the enfeebling luxury and vicious degradation of Roman contemporary life. Such con- trasts for literary effect are especially sought by Tacitus throughout his writings 4, and have often formed part of the common stock of orators and poets, and such an idea had been already touched by Horace⁵ in language showing a sufficiently close resemblance to the thought of Tacitus to suggest some common source of both of themss.
